post.author: bpanjavan
post.title: Silverlight 3 GameBoard using Model-View-Controller
post.content:
Last time I applied Silverlight 3 Unit Testing against a model GameBoard based on given requirements.  The plot now leaps ahead as I use this Model to build a Silverlight 3 application.  This is my first time attempting to apply a Model-View-Controller pattern.  It took longer than if I just quickly cowboy coded a Game Grid and added pieces to it and allowed them to move around, but that's not what my client would want!  Using a separate non-dependent model, I'm hoping this sets the foundation for an ongoing, flexible, and testable project.

If you're in a hurry to see the visual result, here it is:

Let's re-iterate those requirements for a GameBoard:

"A gameboard is a flat plane divided by even sized square spaces.  The gameboard is used to host a game / match between 2 or more teams.  For this scope, we will create gameboard that we can add pieces to and not yet be concerned about teams or the game / match.  Pieces can be moved from space to space.  2 pieces can NOT occupy the same space at the same time."

The Model
From the above we abstract the Model's responsibilities:
  • Provide a means of initiating the GameBoard (*cough* Factory...!)
  • Be able to load itself with a specified number of spaces
  • Pieces can be added to the GameBoard
  • Manage the movement of Pieces
  • Incorporate the concept of selecting spaces
  • When the user selects a space that a piece is on, THEN selects another space, the piece should move to that space, granted that it can
Below is my class diagram of the entire Model.  The main entities are the GameBoard, the Space, and the Piece.  Each has its own interface and base class.


Click to enlarge

Most methods should be pretty self explanatory.  On the IGameBoard interface you'll see the method stubs for implementing the requirements discussed above.  Take very special note at all of the events that are being fired.  From Loaded, to PieceAdded, to PieceMoved, etc..  These events exist to broadcast Model's actions so the Controller and View can listen and respond appropriately

The View

The View's primary responsibility is to listen and respond to the events fired from the Model.  And because the view IS our UI layer, it is responsible for RECEIVING user input and passing it to the Controller.

Here are the View's responsibilities, divided into two categories:

1. Responding to the GameBoard
  • Load a view of the GameBoard when the GameBoard is loaded
  • Add a piece when the GameBoard adds a piece
  • Move a piece when the GameBoard moves a piece
  • Highlight the selected space when a GameBoard space is selected
  • Consequently, clear the selected space when the GameBoard does so
2. Receiving the user input
  • Informing the controller when a space is clicked
Below is my class diagram of the View.  I'm going to apologize ahead of time that I'm not going deep into the Silverlight and XAML implementation just yet.  I'm afraid if I do it's going to digress too far from the main topic, which is the architecture.

Click to enlarge

Note the first five methods are the event handlers that I mentioned above in the View's responsibilities.  They correspond roughly one-to-one with the events fired from the GameBoard model.  Note the 2nd method from the bottom, gamegridMain_SpaceClicked().  This is the one event handler for user input.  See below, this method does nothing more than pass the information along and let the Controller decide how to deal with it.

void gamegridMain_SpaceClicked(object sender,                
        IntrepidPrototype_Grid.Controls.GameGrid.SpaceClickedEventArgs e)
{
    //inform the controller
    _gameBoardController.SpaceClicked(e.LocationX, e.LocationY);
}

The Controller
I thought it was awkward that by the time I finished the controller, it didn't have much to it...not nearly as much as the Model.  But maybe that's how it's supposed to be.  The controller's job is to interpret the view's input, NOT make decisions about the logic of our application.  In my opinion there's a slightly thin line between the two. 

Here are the responsibilities of our Controller in this project:
  • Initiate the View and GameBoard Model
  • Interpret the SpaceClicked event of the View
Our Controller diagram is below:
Click to enlarge

As you can see, this is a relatively thin class.  The constructor will do all of the work of initiating the GameBoard View and Model.  The one event handler, SpaceClicked() will interpret the respective event from the View.
public void SpaceClicked(int locationX, int locationY)
{
    // if a piece is in the middle of moving, do nothing
    if (_gameBoardView.PieceMoving == true)
        return;
    ISpace space = _gameBoardModel.SelectedSpace;
    if (_gameBoardModel.CanMoveToSpace(locationX, locationY))
    {
        _gameBoardModel.MovePiece(space.Piece, locationX, locationY);
        _gameBoardModel.ClearSelectedSpace(); }
    else
    {
        //select the space
        _gameBoardModel.SelectSpace(
                    _gameBoardModel.GetSpace(locationX, locationY));
    }
}

In the above code sample of the Controller, FIRST the controller checks the View to see if a Piece is in the middle of moving.  If so, do nothing.  Then our Controller moves on to ask the Model if the selected Piece can be moved to the location clicked.  If so, the Controller calls the MovePiece() method on our Model and clears the selected space.  Otherwise, the space clicked is selected.

Conclusion
I'd like to address a few clauses of applying Model-View-Controller that I believe MUST be followed:
  • There should be as much MEAT (true business logic) in the model as possible
  • The model must be able to exist independently and hold NO reference to the View OR Controller
  • If the above point is followed, the model should be independently Unit-testable
  • The View's actions must be heavily event driven by the Model's events
  • When receiving input, the View must pass the information along to the Controller and do NOTHING else
  • Truly the View must be RE-active, not PRO-active
  • The Controller is the initiator and manager of the application
  • The Conroller's job is to interpret the input from the View, but NOT make business decisions for the Model

Again here is the final result.
